nsation for a bad start: Grow now, pay later?  Morphological plasticity reduces the effect of poor developmental conditions on fledging age in Mourning Doves  Parent-offspring interactions in Zebra Finches  Ecological immunology: Life history trade-offs and immune defense in birds  Maternal antibodies in a wild altricial bird: Effects on offspring immunity, growth and survival  A flexible growth function for empirical use  Life-history consequences of growth rate depression: An experimental study on Carrion Crows (  Corvus corone  corone L .)  Relative growth, body constituents, and energy content of nestling Barn Swallows and Red-winged Blackbirds  Patterns of growth in birds  Patterns of growth in birds. V. A comparative study of development in the Starling, Common Tern, and Japanese Quail  Water content, thermogenesis, and growth rate of skeletal muscles in the European Starling  Inverse relationship between functional maturity and exponential growth rate of avian skeletal muscle: A constraint on evolutionary response  Developmental plasticity  Effects of early nutrition on growth rate and adult size in Song Sparrows,   Melospiza melodia    Growth rate and function of skeletal muscles in Japanese Quail selected for four-week body mass  Variability of embryo development rate, fry growth, and disease susceptibility in hatchery stocks of chum salmon  Trade-off between immunocompetence and growth in magpies: An experimental study  Patterns of development: The altricial&ndash;precocial spectrum  Resource allocation in fledglings of the Rhinoceros Auklet under different feeding conditions: An experiment manipulating meal size and frequency  Trade-off between growth and immune function: A meta-analysis of selection experiments  Compensatory strategies have evolved in birds to minimize the effects of poor rearing conditions on future survival and fitness. Undernourished nestlings may accelerate growth and/or development relative to age, termed compensatory growth, to achieve normal asymptotic size at the same time as well-fed chicks. While compensatory growth allows birds to fledge at a suitable size and time, it may have persistent detrimental effects on the development of complex body systems. Our study examined compensatory growth following short-term food restriction of caged groups of Zebra Finches (  Taeniopygia guttata  ; adult breeding pair and their brood) during the nestling period, and tested for postrestriction effects on tissue maturity (indexed by body tissue water content) and adaptive immune function. Food restriction reduced nestling body mass, tarsus, and culmen growth. Rapid compensatory growth in body mass, but not in tarsus and culmen lengths, was observed upon return to ad libitum feeding of the food-restricted group. Nestlings that were raised in food-restricted treatment cages showed no significant difference in adaptive antibody response to a model antigen compared with those raised in control cages with ad libitum feeding. Reductions in tissue maturity were observed in nestlings that experienced food restriction, indicating a decoupling of chronological age and physiological age. These data provide evidence of capacity for rapid, compensatory body mass growth in nestling Zebra Finches, and suggest that the energetic costs of body growth and development are relatively larger than the costs of development of the humoral immune system.  Las estrategias de compensaci&oacute;n de las aves han evolucionado para minimizar los efectos de las malas condiciones de cr&iacute;a en la supervivencia futura y en la adecuaci&oacute;n biol&oacute;gica. Los pichones pueden acelerar el crecimiento y/o el desarrollo relativo a la edad, llamado crecimiento compensatorio, para alcanzar un tama&ntilde;o asint&oacute;tico normal al mismo tiempo que las aves bien alimentadas. Mientras que el crecimiento compensatorio permite a las aves dejar el nido con un tama&ntilde;o y en un tiempo adecuados, puede tener efectos persistentes negativos en el desarrollo de los sistemas corporales complejos. Este estudio examina el crecimiento compensatorio luego de breves restricciones de alimento a grupos enjaulaos de   Taeniopygia guttata   (parejas reproductivas de adultos y sus nidadas) durante el per&iacute;odo de nidificaci&oacute;n, y eval&uacute;a los efectos posteriores a la restricci&oacute;n en la madurez del tejido (indexado por el contenido de agua del tejido corporal) y en la funci&oacute;n inmunol&oacute;gica adaptativa. Las restricciones de alimento redujeron la masa corporal de los pichones y el crecimiento del tarso y del culmen. Se observ&oacute; un crecimiento compensatorio r&aacute;pido en la masa corporal, pero no en el largo del tarso y del culmen, como resultado de la alimentaci&oacute;n  ad libitum  del grupo enjaulado. Los pichones criados en las jaulas con tratamientos de restricci&oacute;n de alimentos no mostraron diferencias significativas en la respuesta adaptativa de anticuerpos a un ant&iacute;geno modelo, comparados con aquellos criados en jaulas control con alimentaci&oacute;n  ad libitum . Se observaron reducciones en la madurez de los tejidos en pichones que tuvieron un tratamiento con restricci&oacute;n de alimentos, indicando un desacople de la edad cronol&oacute;gica y la edad fisiol&oacute;gica. Estos datos brindan evidencia de una capacidad de crecimiento y compensaci&oacute;n de masa corporal r&aacute;pida en los pichones de   T. guttata   y sugiere que los costos energ&eacute;ticos del crecimiento corporal y del desarrollo son relativamente mayores que los costos de desarrollo del sistema inmunol&oacute;gico humoral.   Palabras clave:  anticuerpos, hemocianina, madurez del tejido, plasticidad de desarrollo, recuperaci&oacute;n del crecimiento, restricciones de alimento,   Taeniopygia guttata    Periods of food restriction can be a common occurrence for growing altricial birds, which hatch in a relatively undeveloped state and rely on parental delivery of food during the nestling period ( Starck and Ricklefs 1998 ). Compensatory strategies have evolved to minimize the effects of poor rearing conditions on future survival and fitness ( Schew and Ricklefs 1998 ). Birds experiencing slowed growth and/or development resulting from resource limitation may extend the growth and developmental periods to achieve asymptotic size ( Schew and Ricklefs 1998 ). Alternatively, once food becomes freely available, birds may accelerate growth and/or development relative to age, termed compensatory growth, to achieve normal asymptotic size at the same time as well-fed birds ( Schew and Ricklefs 1998 ,  Hector and Nakagawa 2012 ).  While compensatory growth allows birds to fledge at a suitable size and time, it may have persistent detrimental effects ( Metcalfe and Monaghan 2001 ). Early resource limitation during the nestling period of Zebra Finches (  Taeniopygia guttata  ) was associated with reduced postfledging survival ( DeKogel 1997 ) and reduced lifespan ( Birkhead et al. 1999 ), despite birds attaining similar sizes to well-fed controls as adults. Zebra Finch females that demonstrated rapid growth following a switch from a low-quality to a high-quality rearing diet as nestlings later demonstrated decreased flight performance as reproductive adults ( Criscuolo et al. 2011 ). Reduced flight performance may reflect reduced muscle tissue differentiation resulting from catch-up growth during the nestling phase, as has been observed in Japanese Quail (  Coturnix japonica  ) that were artificially selected for rapid growth ( Shea et al. 1995 ). In Zebra Finches, compensatory growth has been shown to result in reduced cognitive function ( Fisher et al. 2006 ), increased susceptibility to oxidative damage ( Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2007 ), and elevated adult resting metabolic rates ( Criscuolo et al. 2008 ). These phenotypic effects may be manifestations of oxidative stress or altered development of complex tissue and organ systems due to accelerated body growth ( Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2007 ,  Criscuolo et al. 2008 ).  Compensatory growth may alter another complex system, the immune system, and tradeoffs may occur if resources are allocated to rapid growth at the expense of immune system development following food restriction ( Norris and Evans 2000 ). Artificial selection for rapid growth has been linked to decreased immune function and increased pathogen susceptibility in a variety of taxa, including mice, salmon, turkeys, and chickens ( Bradford and Famula 1984 ,  Smoker 1986 ,  Bayyari et al. 1997 ,  van der Most et al. 2011 ). However, the effects of early food restriction and compensatory growth on adaptive immune function in Zebra Finches and other nondomesticated passerines has not been extensively studied. Development of adaptive humoral components in birds is purportedly costly, as it requires generation and proliferation of B-cell lineages with diverse, functional antibody specificities ( Lee 2006 ). Because altricial birds develop capacity for adaptive antibody response during the early weeks after hatching ( Grindstaff et al. 2006 ,  Pihlaja et al. 2006 ,  King et al. 2010 ,  Killpack and Karasov 2012b ,  Killpack et al. 2013 ), food restriction and compensatory growth of nestlings may reduce the ability to mount diverse functional antibody responses later in life.  We examined compensatory growth and tested for its effects on body composition and adaptive immune function development in captive, altricial Zebra Finches. Previous studies of compensatory growth in Zebra Finches ( Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2007 ,  Criscuolo et al. 2008 ,  2011 ,  Fisher et al. 2006 ,  Krause and Naguib 2011 ) examined the effects of inadequate feeding conditions (e.g., enlarged brood sizes, low-quality diets) lasting the majority or entirety of the nestling period, and measured subsequent growth responses over a 15-day or longer refeeding period postfledging. Because Zebra Finches have determinate growth, and rapidly reach adult size during the first two weeks of the 21-day nestling period ( Brz&eogon;k et al. 2010 ), we examined the capacity for rapid compensatory growth following an ecologically relevant food-restriction period during this time (6&ndash;9 days posthatch). We then used two criteria to evaluate compensatory growth upon return to ad libitum feeding of the experimental group: accelerated growth rate in the previously food-restricted nestlings compared with controls in the first 72 hr of refeeding (9&ndash;12 days posthatch), and whether food-restricted nestlings reached the same asymptotic size at the same time as controls. We chose two criteria because there is no uniform or consensus protocol in the literature for demonstrating compensatory growth (cf.  Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2007 ,  Bize et al. 2006 ,  Lepczyk and Karasov 2000 ), and because both of these criteria corresponded well operationally to the concept. Based on studies of animals artificially selected for rapid growth, we predicted that tissue maturation and adaptive antibody response would be reduced in nestlings demonstrating compensatory growth. This is the first study of a rapidly growing altricial bird to test both for compensatory growth entirely during the nestling period and for an associated effect on immunity when nestlings are still developing adult-level capacity for adaptive antibody production.  Zebra Finches in a breeding colony at the University of Wisconsin&ndash;Madison, Wisconsin, USA, were maintained under standardized conditions of 14 hr:10 hr light:dark photoperiod (lights on at 0600 hr), 21&ndash;24&deg;C temperature, and 40&ndash;50&percnt; relative humidity. Breeding pairs of adult Zebra Finches were placed in individual breeding cages and provided with nesting material, a nest box, cuttlefish bone (calcium source), grit, and water ad libitum. Breeding pairs were also provided ad libitum with seed mix (by mass, 70&percnt; commercial seeds and 30&percnt; food supplement; Mazuri Small Bird Breeder,  www.mazuri.com ). Pairs were additionally provided with enrichment foods of green vegetables and an egg-food mixture (hard-boiled eggs with shells, dried egg food &lsqb;Volkman Featherglow; Volkman Seed Company, Ceres, CA&rsqb;, and liquid vitamin and mineral supplements &lsqb;Vetafarm Products, Australia&rsqb;) three times per week. Upon hatching of the first chick, enrichment feeding ceased. There was no food restriction during the egg-laying period.  In Zebra Finches, nestlings hatch asynchronously, and are fed by regurgitation of food by both male and female parent birds ( Muller and Smith 1978 ). We imposed food restriction by manipulating the quantity of seed mix available to adult pairs to feed to their broods. This method allowed for resource allocation during restriction and realimentation to occur in the ecologically relevant context of parental feeding behavior. Broods were culled to have a maximum of three nestlings, although some pairs successfully hatched only one or two nestlings. Limiting brood size to three nestlings increases the probability that all nestlings in a brood are evenly fed each feeding bout, and reduces nestling mortality not associated with feeding treatment (deKogel 1997,  Gilby et al. 2011 ). There was no significant difference in brood size between control (2.54 &plusmn; 0.2 nestlings) and food-restricted cage groups (2.17 &plusmn; 0.2 nestlings;  t  22  &equals; 1.34,  P  &equals; 0.19).  Cage groups were randomly assigned to either control or food-restricted experimental treatment upon hatching of the first chick. Control groups were fed ad libitum for the duration of the experiment (ad libitum feeding: experiment day &minus;6 to 16). Because Zebra Finches hatch asynchronously, the timing of food restriction in the experimental treatment groups was determined using the average age of nestlings in each experimental brood. Experimental treatment groups were fed seed mix ad libitum from hatch until an average brood age of 6 days posthatch (ad libitum feeding: experiment day &minus;6 to 0). Food restriction in experimental treatment groups began when the average brood age was 6 days posthatch. At this time, experimental treatment groups were restricted to 70&percnt; of ad libitum seed mix for a 72 hr duration (food restriction: experiment day 0 to 3). The imposed food restriction level of 70&percnt; of ad libitum quantity was calculated based on the percentage of seed mix that was edible food (i.e. not seed hulls) and the average daily food consumption in the three days prior to experiment day 0. Following the 72 hr restriction, experimental treatment groups were returned to ad libitum feeding until the end of the experiment (ad libitum feeding: experiment day 3 to 16).  There was no significant difference in average nestling age at experiment day 0 between control (5.9 &plusmn; 0.1 days) and food-restricted (6.0 &plusmn; 0.1 days) broods ( t  57  &equals; 1.34,  P  &gt; 0.8). If adult pairs had multiple broods, experimental treatment assignments were alternated. The control treatment was applied to a total of 33 nestlings in 13 broods from 9 parental pairs, and the food-restriction treatment was applied to a total of 26 nestlings in 12 broods from 9 parental pairs.  Cage groups were visited every day between 1400 and 1600 hr CST. Although we did not directly quantify parental feeding effort, we quantified the daily food intake of the cage groups and the body measures of nestlings and adults to track allocation of food resources. Body mass of nestlings and adults (&plusmn;0.01 g) and tarsus and culmen lengths of nestlings (&plusmn;0.10 mm using digital calipers) were measured during daily visits from experiment day &minus;6 to 16. After these body measurements had been taken, all seeds were collected from each cage, fecal matter was removed, and daily food consumption for the cage was calculated (seed mass provided the previous day minus orts, i.e. remaining seed mass).  For a subset of nestlings, we tested the effect of food restriction on immune function after refeeding (control:  n  &equals; 17, food-restricted:  n  &equals; 13). Antibody production, a component of adaptive immunity, was induced by modifying a previously described method ( Killpack and Karasov 2012b ). Briefly, on experiment day 13 (average brood age: 19 days posthatch), nestlings were injected intramuscularly in the pectoralis muscle with a 50 &mu;l primary injection of 25 &mu;l of keyhole limpet hemocyanin (KLH) antigen (Calbiochem, San Diego, California, USA) diluted in phosphate buffered saline (PBS) at a dose of 1.0 &mu;g antigen per g body mass emulsified with 25 &mu;l Titermax adjuvant (Titermax USA, Norcross, Georgia, USA). A blood sample was taken 7 days after primary injection (experiment day 20; average brood age: 26 days posthatch) by puncturing the brachial vein with a 28-gauge needle and collecting the blood into heparinized microcapillary tubes. Following collection of the primary blood sample, nestlings were boosted with the same dose of KLH emulsified with Titermax adjuvant, and a postboost blood sample was taken 7 days later (experiment day 27; average brood age: 33 days posthatch). Blood samples were centrifuged and plasma was stored at &minus;80&deg;C until enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) analysis of KLH-specific antibodies was performed. After the postboost blood sample was taken, all nestlings were euthanized with CO 2  and carcasses were frozen for later use. All experimental procedures were designed to minimize sample size and distress of the birds (see Ethics statement in the Acknowledgments).  The intestines of all nestling carcasses were removed for use in a separate study. The wet carcass mass (without intestines) was measured and carcasses were individually wrapped in preweighed, labeled filter paper. Carcass packets were dried to constant mass in a 65&deg;C drying oven, dry masses were recorded, and water mass (g wet tissue &minus; g dry tissue) was calculated. The skulls were then cracked to allow ether to penetrate the skull cavity, and lipids were extracted from the carcass packets using diethyl ether in a modified Soxhlet side-arm extractor. Lean dry mass, lipid mass extracted (g dry tissue &minus; g lean dry tissue), and indices of tissue water content (g water/g lean dry tissue) and tissue lipid content (g lipid extracted/g lean dry tissue) were recorded.  Adaptive immune function was measured using a previously described ELISA for detection of KLH-specific immunoglobulin Y (IgY) antibodies ( Killpack and Karasov 2012b ), with the following modifications: After addition of ABTS (2,2&prime;-azino-bis(3-ethylbanzo-thiazoline-6-sulfonic acid)) substrate, plates were incubated in the dark at room temperature for 15 min, and 100 &mu;l of 1&percnt; sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) solution was added to all wells before optical densities were read.  Results are given as means &plusmn; SE ( n  &equals; number of individuals). All tests were carried out using R statistical package ( R Development Core Team 2008 ), except for nonlinear curve-fitting to growth models, which was performed in SYSTAT ( Wilkinson 2000 ). Parametric tests were used when data were normal or could be transformed to an approximately normal distribution. For all tests, the significance level was set at  P  &lt; 0.05, and 0.05 &lt;  P  &lt; 0.10 was considered to indicate a trend.  We fit linear mixed models of food consumption using maximum likelihood criteria, with day, treatment, and their interaction as fixed effects. Pair ID and brood ID were included as random effects to control for repeated measures and for nonindependence of our samples (i.e. feeding treatment imposed on cage families) to avoid pseudoreplication. Single-term deletion chi-square-based tests were used to determine the significance of individual interaction and fixed effect predictors (as in  Killpack et al. 2013 ). Post hoc analyses were performed for models with significant interactions using simultaneous tests for general linear hypotheses and defined contrasts of treatment differences in food consumption on a given experiment day. Two-sample  t -tests were used to compare treatment differences in changes in body measures over the 72-hr experimental period (experiment day 0 to 3) for broods of nestlings or pairs of adults.  Two criteria were used to evaluate compensatory growth in food-restricted Zebra Finch nestlings: whether there were accelerated growth rates following restriction, and whether the same asymptotic size was achieved at the same time as control-fed nestlings. Using these two criteria for compensatory growth evaluation required that attainment of control body size in food-restricted nestlings be achieved through faster-than-normal growth rates. This contrasts with &lsquo;catch-up' growth achieved through normal growth rates and an extended developmental period ( Hector and Nakagawa 2012 ).  Growth rates (g day &minus;1  or mm day &minus;1 ) were calculated for 72 hr prior to food restriction (Pre), 72 hr during food restriction (Restriction), and 72 hr following food restriction (Post). We fit linear mixed models for each 72 hr period using maximum likelihood criteria, with treatment as a fixed effect and pair ID and brood ID as random effects to control for repeated measures and nonindependence of our samples (i.e. relatedness of siblings in a nest). Single-term deletion chi-square-based tests were then used to determine whether there were significant treatment differences in growth rate for that period. We also examined treatment effects on growth rates while including size at the start of each period as a covariate in the mixed models.  To test for asymptotic size and the time when it was reached, we performed nonlinear curve-fitting of empirical control data using the Richards equation to fit body mass data ( Richards 1959 ; shape parameter value: 2.5) and the logistic growth equation fit to tarsus and culmen data. Both equations have been used to describe growth in passeriform species ( Lepczyk and Karasov 2000 ,  Ricklefs 1968 ) and we chose equations based on least-squares criteria. We calculated the average asymptotic size (g or mm) and 95&percnt; confidence interval from the nonlinear curve models of all control nestlings. We then used empirical data to determine the day that control and food-restricted nestlings reached the modeled asymptotic size, and used a two-sample  t -test to compare the mean day that asymptotic size was reached between treatment groups.  For the analysis of treatment differences in nestling body composition, we fit linear mixed models and used single-term deletion chi-square-based tests as described above. Wilcoxon rank sum nonparametric tests were used to examine treatment differences in KLH-specific antibody responses after the primary and booster injections. Paired  t -tests were used to compare KLH antibody responses after the primary vs. booster injection within each treatment group.  Food consumption significantly differed between treatment groups only during the imposed 72-hr food-restriction period (day &times; treatment interaction: &chi; 2  &equals; 102,  P  &lt; 0.001;  P  &lt; 0.001 for daily contrasts of food consumption on experiment days 1, 2, 3). During the 72-hr food-restriction period, seed consumption in the experimental groups (6.25 &plusmn; 0.28 g day &minus;1 ) averaged 46&percnt; less than control group consumption (11.55 &plusmn; 0.39 g day &minus;1 ). Both sexes of the parent Zebra Finches fed their nestlings, and there was a significant difference in body mass change over the 72-hr experimental period between adult pairs in control and food-restricted cages. While adults feeding nestlings in ad libitum control cages showed only a 1&percnt; reduction in body mass during the 72-hr experimental period (&minus;0.14 &plusmn; 0.33 g from experiment day 0 to 3), there was an 8&percnt; reduction in body mass of adults in experimentally food-restricted cages during this 72-hr period (&minus;0.91 &plusmn; 0.68 g from experiment day 0 to 3;  t  14  &equals; 3.46,  P  &equals; 0.004).  Decreased food intake in food-restricted cages over the 72-hr experimental period was associated with significant reductions in growth of nestling broods compared with broods in control cages. Broods in control ad libitum feeding cages exhibited a 43&percnt; increase in body mass over the 72-hr experimental period (3.47 &plusmn; 0.28 g from experiment day 0 to 3), but broods in food-restricted cages showed only an 18&percnt; increase in body mass during this time (0.96 &plusmn; 0.22 g from experiment day 0 to 3;  t  22  &equals; 7.34,  P  &lt; 0.001;  Figure 1 A). Broods in control ad libitum cages exhibited a 30&percnt; increase in tarsus length over the 72-hr experimental period (3.47 &plusmn; 0.38 mm from experiment day 0 to 3), whereas broods in food-restricted cages showed only a 21&percnt; increase in tarsus length during this time (1.93 &plusmn; 0.46 mm from experiment day 0 to 3;  t  22  &equals; 2.70,  P  &equals; 0.013;  Figure 2 A). Broods in control ad libitum cages exhibited a 25&percnt; increase in culmen length over the 72-hr experimental period (1.20 &plusmn; 0.20 mm from experiment day 0 to 3), while broods in food-restricted cages showed only a 15&percnt; increase in culmen length during this time (0.63 &plusmn; 0.15 mm from experiment day 0 to 3;  t  22  &equals; 2.41,  P  &equals; 0.02;  Figure 3 A).  ( A ) Body masses of control (filled triangles) and food-restricted (unfilled circles) Zebra Finch nestlings. Food restriction (denoted by white box on  x -axis) occurred from experiment day 1 (average brood age &equals; 6 days posthatch) through experiment day 3. Data are means &plusmn; SE. ( B ) Body mass growth rates of Zebra Finch nestlings during the 72 hr prerestriction (Pre; experiment days &minus;2, &minus;1, 0), food restriction (Restriction; experiment days 1, 