was achieved at the same time as control-fed nestlings. Both criteria for compensatory growth in body mass were met by food-restricted nestlings. Body mass growth rates did not significantly differ between treatments prerestriction (&chi; 2  &equals; 0.001,  P  &equals; 0.98), were significantly lower in food-restricted birds during restriction (&chi; 2  &equals; 33,  P  &lt; 0.001), and were significantly higher in food-restricted birds postrestriction (&chi; 2  &equals; 9.68,  P  &equals; 0.002;  Figure 1 B). Mean modeled asymptotic body mass, calculated using Richards' (1959) equation fit to individual control nestling growth curves, was 12.09 g (95&percnt; confidence interval: 11.80 g, 12.39 g). The experiment day when asymptotic size was reached did not significantly differ between control (9.8 &plusmn; 0.75 days) and food-restricted nestlings (11.8 &plusmn; 1.2 days;  t  30  &equals; &minus;1.40,  P  &equals; 0.15), and experimental nestlings reached the modeled asymptotic body mass prior to fledging age (21 days posthatch, or experiment day 15;  Figure 1 A).  In contrast to body mass growth, the dual criteria for compensatory tarsus growth were not met in food-restricted nestlings. No accelerated tarsus growth was observed following food restriction. Tarsus growth rates did not significantly differ between treatments during prerestriction (&chi; 2  &equals; 3.63,  P  &equals; 0.06), were significantly lower in food-restricted nestlings during restriction (&chi; 2 &equals; 8.99,  P  &equals; 0.003), and did not significantly differ between treatments postrestriction (&chi; 2  &equals; 2.19,  P  &equals; 0.14;  Figure 2 B). Although prerestriction tarsus growth was slightly lower in the food-restricted group, neither the interaction of prerestriction tarsus growth rate with treatment (&chi; 2  &equals; 0.10,  P  &equals; 0.75) nor the fixed effect of prerestriction tarsus growth rate (&chi; 2  &equals; 0.62,  P  &equals; 0.43) had a significant effect on postre