reach the modeled asymptotic culmen length by the end of the experimental period were in the immune subset, and their culmen sizes were compared at the time of euthanization. When measured at experiment day 27, there were no significant differences in culmen length between the subsets of control (8.85 &plusmn; 0.12 mm,  n  &equals; 12) and food-restricted nestlings (8.78 &plusmn; 0.09 mm,  n  &equals; 13;  t  21  &equals; 0.51,  P  &equals; 0.62).  A subset of nestlings from the compensatory growth experiment (control  n  &equals; 17 and food-restricted  n  &equals; 13) were analyzed for adaptive immune function and body composition following refeeding. KLH-specific antibody responses of birds in both treatments increased between sampling following the primary injection (on experiment day 13) and the booster injection (on experiment day 20;  t  28  &equals; &minus;3.24,  P  &equals; 0.003;  Figure 4 ), providing evidence of significant secondary IgY antibody response to the booster in both control and food-restricted groups. However, there was no significant difference between control and food-restricted birds in KLH-specific primary antibody response 7 days after the primary injection ( z  &equals; 98,  P  &equals; 0.81) or in secondary antibody response 7 days after the booster injection ( z  &equals; 109,  P  &equals; 0.97;  Figure 4 ). There was no significant correlation between postbooster KLH response and growth rate during the three days postrestriction within the food-restricted group ( r  &equals; 0.45,  t  11  &equals; 1.68,  P  &equals; 0.12) or the control group ( r  &equals; 0.18,  t  15  &equals; 0.69,  P  &equals; 0.50).  Specific antibody responses of control (filled bars) and food-restricted (unfilled bars) Zebra Finch nestlings injected intramuscularly with keyhole limpet hemocyanin (KLH) antigen. Data are means &plusmn; SE. Asterisks indicate a significant difference between postvaccination and postboost antibody response levels (&ast;&ast;  P  &lt; 0.01). No significant treatment effect was observed between control and food-restricted groups.  There were no significant differences in lean dry mass between control (2.89 &plusmn; 0.13 g) and food-restricted (2.82 &plusmn; 0.09 g) nestlings at the end of the experimental period(&chi; 2  &equals; 0.331,  P  &equals; 0.57). Lean body water content (g water per g lean dry mass) was significantly higher in food-restricted nestlings (2.59 &plusmn; 0.02) compared with controls (2.46 &plusmn; 0.02; &chi; 2  &equals; 12.70,  P  &lt; 0.001). Body lipid content (g lipid per g lean dry mass) did not significantly differ between food-restricted nestlings (0.42 &plusmn; 0.02) and controls (0.39 &plusmn; 0.02; &chi; 2  &equals; 1.17,  P  &equals; 0.28).  Our food restriction protocol significantly reduced nestling growth, and we demonstrated rapid compensatory body mass growth in nestling Zebra Finches upon return to ad libitum feeding. We observed accelerated growth rates in food-restricted nestlings in the 72 hr following restriction, and the same asymptotic body mass was reached on the same experimental day as controls. Food-restricted nestlings did not significantly differ from controls in lean dry-body mass at the end of the experiment, providing additional evidence that the compensatory growth in body mass likely represented functional lean tissue mass gain rather than increased lipid stores. This capacity to accelerate body mass growth lends support to the theory that normal body growth under typical feeding conditions is regulated at an optimized, rather than maximized, rate ( Metcalfe and Monaghan 2001 ). While compensatory growth in Zebra Finches has been previously reported ( Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2007 ,  Fisher et al. 2006 ,  Criscuolo et al. 2008 ,  2011 ,  Krause and Naguib 2011 ), ours is the first study, to our knowledge, to demonstrate accelerated compensatory growth in Zebra Finch nestlings within a few days following food restriction. Previous studies have presented mixed results regarding compensatory body mass growth after short-term food restriction in altricial nestlings. Laboratory studies using hand-feeding to impose short-term food restrictions on House Sparrow (  Passer domesticus  ;  Lepczyk and Karasov 2000 ), Song Thrush (  Turdus philomelos  ;  Konarzewski et al. 1996 ), and Bank Swallow (  Riparia riparia  ;  Brz&eogon;k and Konarzewski 2001 ) nestlings did not find evidence of compensatory growth in body mass upon refeeding of the birds. In contrast, free-living altricial Alpine Swift (  Apus melba  ;  Bize et al. 2006 ) and Collared Flycatcher (  Ficedula albicollis  ;  Hegyi and T&ouml;r&ouml;k 2007 ) nestlings experiencing short-term food restriction demonstrated accelerated rates of body mass growth upon return to improved feeding conditions. Models utilizing parents to feed nestlings, whether in the wild ( Bize et al. 2006 ,  Hegyi and T&ouml;r&ouml;k 2007 ) or in the laboratory (our study), may therefore be better experimental models for comparative studies of capacity for nestling compensatory growth.  In contrast to body mass growth, we observed near-parallel, rather than accelerated, tarsus growth rates in Zebra Finch nestlings during the immediate refeeding period. There was no significant increase in tarsus growth rate in food-restricted birds in the 72 hr following food restriction, although control and food-restricted birds reached the same asymptotic size at the same time. Thus, following food restriction, control tarsus size was achieved in the absence of accelerated growth rates ( Hector and Nakagawa 2012 ). Sternum size reductions in Alpine Swifts experiencing a one-week period of undernutrition were not recovered until 30 days following food restriction, demonstrating slow growth to asymptotic sternum size ( Bize et al. 2006 ). In 7-day-old Collared Flycatchers, tarsus length reductions following a 3-day food restriction were not recovered by fledging age at 4 days postrestriction ( Hegyi and T&ouml;r&ouml;k 2007 ). Lack of accelerated skeletal growth may reflect the strong endocrine control of long-bone growth ( Leach and Rosselot 1992 ), which may impose a critical rate and time window for structural growth. It is ecologically advantageous for structural size to be achieved prior to fledging, as decreased structural size can have negative implications for fledging time ( Miller 2010 ,  Searcy et al. 2004 ), social rank ( Richner et al. 1989 ), and recruitment ( Emlen and Wrege 1991 ). Because restriction occurred early in the nestling period, food-restricted Zebra Finches appeared to reach control tarsus length prior to fledging without significantly accelerating their growth rates ( Figure 2 ). However, if food restriction had occurred later in the nestling period, control tarsus size may not have been reached prior to fledging. Future studies should examine the impact of the timing and magnitude of food restriction during the nestling period on patterns of subsequent growth of body mass and skeletal structures ( Bize et al. 2006 ).  Reduced culmen growth rates in food-restricted Zebra Finches persisted in the 72 hr after return to ad libitum feeding. Slow catch-up of reduced culmen length did occur during the weeks postfledging ( Hector and Nakagawa 2012 ); food-restricted birds in the immune subset did not have significantly shorter average culmen lengths compared with controls on experiment day 27 (average age 33 days posthatch). It is possible that accelerated compensatory body mass growth postrestriction came at the cost of a reduction in culmen growth rates. Apparent tradeoffs between body mass and culmen growth may be related to relatively slow growth to asymptotic size of the culmen and skull compared with other skeletal components. In a study of growth in Red-winged Blackbirds (  Agelaius phoeniceus  ), the head was shown to have a relatively low postnatal growth constant compared with other body components such as the wings and digestive organs ( Ricklefs 1967 ). In Marbled Murrelets (  Brachyramphus marmoratus  ), bill growth continued to increase significantly after nest departure, and bill length was positively influenced by the quality of the postfledging (at-sea) diet ( Janssen et al. 2011 ). Future studies of structure-specific tradeoffs in growth should include culmen and skull measurements and consider fitness effects of reduced culmen and skull growth.  Given the evidence that many animals are capable of growing at faster rates than they generally display, it is possible that the benefits of always maximizing growth rate may be outweighed by other physiological and/or ecological costs ( Metcalfe and Monaghan 2001 ). Compensatory growth in Zebra Finches has been associated with reduced cognitive ability ( Fisher et al. 2006 ), reduced flight performance ( Criscuolo et al. 2011 ), increased susceptibility to oxidative damage ( Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2007 ), and elevated adult resting metabolic rates ( Criscuolo et al. 2008 ). In our study we examined tissue maturity in Zebra Finches demonstrating compensatory growth. Tissue maturity is commonly indexed by lean tissue water content ( Marsh and Wickler 1982 ,  Choi et al. 1993 ), because reductions in muscle water content occur with age and coincide with increasing muscle function in birds ( Ricklefs and Webb 1985 ). In previous studies of altricial and semialtricial birds, no significant increases in muscle water content were observed during food restriction ( Burness et al. 2000 ,  Dahdul and Horn 2003 ,  Killpack and Karasov 2012a ,  Konarzewski et al. 1996 ,  Takenaka et al. 2005 ). In contrast, following food restriction and compensatory growth, Zebra Finches in our study had significantly higher lean tissue water content, and thus decreased tissue maturity, compared with controls. Therefore, it appears that a tradeoff between growth and development occurred as result of accelerated growth during the nestling period, resulting in a decoupling of chronological age and physiological age in food-restricted birds. Acquisition of functional maturity through rapid cellular differentiation could limit the proportion of tissue capable of cell proliferation and growth, and this antagonism might constrain postnatal growth and development ( Ricklefs 1979 ). For example, exponential growth rate of muscles has been negatively correlated with indices of glycolytic activity, electric potential, and contractile protein content in birds ( Ricklefs et al. 1994 ). Delayed tissue differentiation resulting from compensatory growth could have negative effects on maintenance metabolism and thermogenesis, as well as flight performance (which has been observed in Zebra Finches following compensatory growth;  Criscuolo et al. 2011 ) in adults. Food-restricted Zebra Finches in our study did not differ from controls in body lipid content; this finding is in agreement with another study of birds refed after food restriction ( Brz&eogon;k and Konarzewski 2004 ). These patterns suggest that while developmental maturation of the tissues may be suspended or delayed as a result of compensatory growth, the ability to recover depleted fat stores resulting from food restriction is more flexible.  An apparent tradeoff between investment in growth and investment in immune response has been observed in free-living nestlings ( Soler et al. 2003 ,  Brommer 2004 ,  Mauck et al. 2005 ,  Arriero et al. 2013 ) and in food-restricted nestlings in the laboratory ( Brz&eogon;k and Konarzewski 2007 ). To our knowledge, this is the first study to examine the effects of accelerated, compensatory growth on adaptive humoral immune development in Zebra Finches or rapidly growing altricial birds in general. Development of adaptive humoral components is purportedly costly because it requires generation and proliferation of B-cell lineages with diverse, functional antibody specificities ( Lee 2006 ). However, food restriction and accelerated growth did not alter development of the humoral immune system or the capacity for functional memory antibody response in our current study. Previously food-restricted Zebra Finches mounted functional secondary antibody responses to a booster KLH injection, and the magnitude of the response did not significantly differ from that of controls. Additionally, neither the previously food-restricted birds nor the control birds showed a significant correlation between postrestriction growth rate and the adaptive antibody response level, reinforcing the absence of a tradeoff between growth and development of adaptive immune capacity. Together, these data suggest that the energetic costs of growth are relatively larger than the costs of development of the humoral immune system ( van der Most et al. 2011 ,  Hasselquist and Nilsson 2012 ), and that tradeoffs in adaptive antibody response may not be expected following rapid growth. To further examine tradeoffs in immune function and growth, future studies should examine the effects of varied timing and duration of food stress, as well as the immune impacts of food restriction alone and restriction followed by compensatory growth ( Metcalfe and Monaghan 2001 ).  In conclusion, experimentally decreased food availability in cage groups for 72 hr led to reduced body mass and structural growth in nestling Zebra Finches fed by parents. Using two criteria (accelerated growth rates in the first 72 hr of refeeding and attainment of the same asymptotic size at the same time as controls), we demonstrated compensatory growth in body mass, but not tarsus or culmen length, in previously food-restricted nestlings. Nestlings raised in the experimental feeding treatment had significantly reduced tissue maturity, but no significant alterations in adaptive antibody response, when compared with control nestlings.  All experimental procedures were approved by the University of Wisconsin&ndash;Madison Animal Care and Use Committee (Permit No. 1421). We thank 